Modify the tutorial pytorch model to achieve better results.

# This is the final model that we executed. The intermediate changes we made are available in lab8part4 jupyter notebook.
class ConvNet(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, num_classes=10):
        super(ConvNet, self).__init__()
        self.layer1 = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Conv2d(1, 16, kernel_size=5, stride=1, padding=2),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(16),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)
        )
        self.layer2 = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Conv2d(16, 32, kernel_size=5, stride=1, padding=2),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(32),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)
        )
        
        
        
        ############################################################################################################################
        #New layer added is the first modification (iteration 1)
        self.layer3 = nn.Sequential( # Added a new convolution layer
            nn.Conv2d(32, 64, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding=1),
            nn.BatchNorm2d(64),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)
        )
        
        ############################################################################################################################
        #2nd iteration - We increased the number of neurons in fully connected layer to 256
        self.fc = nn.Linear(3 * 3 * 64, 256)
        
        ############################################################################################################################
        #We added a dropout layer of 0.25 to add more generalization in the model and to avoid overfitting - 3rd iteration
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(0.25)  
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(256, num_classes)

    def forward(self, x):
        out = self.layer1(x)
        out = self.layer2(out)
        out = self.layer3(out)
        out = out.view(out.size(0), -1)
        out = nn.functional.relu(self.fc(out))
        out = self.dropout(out)  # Applied dropout after the first fully connected layer
        out = self.fc2(out)
        return out

# Instantiate the model
model2 = ConvNet(num_classes).to(device)

Discuss any achieved performance improvement. List the changes you have made.

1. The 1st iteration we made was to add a new convolution layer 3. The rationale behind increasing the number of layers is to train the model on more intricate details of the image. Deeper Layer levels help us find more abstract features in the image dataset and this leads to better perofrmance on new unseen test data. This layer was added to increase model complexity. The 3rd layer included Batch Normalization and MaxPooling layer with a padding and stride of 2. The kernel for convolution was of 3x3. Finally the activation function used was RelU. This mode achieved us 99.27% training accuracy whereas 99.14% accuracy on the validation dataset. ...
2. The 2nd iteration we did was by increasing the number of neurons in fully connected layer to 256. Increasing the number of neurons allows the network to capture more complex and nuanced patterns in the data. Different neurons specialize in recognizing different features, and a richer set of features can be learned with a larger number of neurons. Another fully connected layer is also added which gets us an accuracy of 100% on training set and on test set it gets an accuracy of 99.28%. This is a signficant improvement on the test set. Therefore, we see that this change is useful for better model training and better perforamnce on validation dataset. ...
3. Finally the 3rd iteration we did was by adding drop out. Drop out means to turn off a few neurons or to set some of the input units to zero during the training on training data set. This allows the network less reliance on specific neurons and therefore leads better generalization and to avoid overfitting on the training dataset and perform better generalization so that the bias variance trade off is as such that there is low bias and relatively low variance. The model is expected to perform better on test set. We did a 0.25 drop out and the training accuracy we got 99.89% which is lower than previous model since we added drop out hence it is not overfit on training data. The validation set accuracy is 99.32 which is higher since there is better generalization on the entire dataset. ...

Discussion:

As we see here, we make 3 modifications for our new model. The modifications as discussed above included addition of new layer, addition of neurons in fully connected layer and a dropout of 0.25.

We see by the table that the training accuracy accuracy increases when we add new layers and neurons. This goes on to show that as we increase model complexity and add more filters/neurons in the CNN model, more intricate details of the images are captured and therefore, the accuracy of the training set increases since the model is more complex and deep. Similarly we see that the accuracy on testing data set also increases gradually from 98.96% to 99.10% by the first two modifications which shows us that the model is more complex now and can perform better on unseen test data.

We finally add a dropout of 0.25 which means we set some of the neurons to 0 to train the model. We see that our training accuracy decreases from 99.32% to 99.08% which shows that the model is less good on the trained data set. This is the primary goal of dropout which is to generalize the data and avoid overfitting. The model should be considerably good on training data but if its overly sensitive to training data, it behaves bad on test data. The test data in modification 3 has a tersting accuracy of 99.21% with an increase of 0.11% which tells us that although the model is not perfectly accurate on training data, it is highly accurate on testing data showing that better generealization has been achieved.

The model's accuracy of 98.96% from the original model increased to 99.21% after making all 3 changes to the model. We have also tested the model iteratively with accuracies at each step. The accuracy has increased at each step

Discusssion

Make at least three significant observations from teh above table

1. The first observation is the time and epochs consumed by Keras and PyTorch models to converge and get a higher training accuracy. We see that training time in Keras models is substantially high with an avg time of 1080 whereas for PyTorch models, the avg time is around 440. Despite the fact that PyTorch runs for lower number of epochs, it still reaches to a substantially high training and testing accuracy which is comparable to Keras. Therefore, it is wise to train on PyTorch to achieve high accuracy of the model with lower number of epochs and hence less computationally intesnive to save computation costs.

2. The new custom model does not achieve the highest training accuracy but it definitely achieves the highest testing accuracy among all models. This reflects that we have a trade off between overfitting and generalization. The models we used before had lower testing accuracy but higher training accuracy and a possibility of this is that the models were not deep networks and they were not good at generlizing. We see the important of dropout and making the model more complex as it tends to prevent overfitting and leads to a better accuracy on the test dataset which is unseen. A proof of this is that when we tested our own dataset of images on both the old and the new custom model, we got a training acccuracy of 81.7% on the custom model and 80% on the old model which tells that it performs better on new test dataset compared to the old model.

3. The third observation is that for convolutional its is highly important to add Batch normalization and maxpooling. batch normalization helps in normalizing the mean and variance of the input to each layer whereas maxpooling helps in compoutational efficiency by reducing parameters. As we see in model K1, the testing and training accuracy are lower as compared to the model K2. THere's a substantial difference because in model K1 for the first layer of convolution there is no batch normalization and maxpooling performed therefore, the time taken to train the model is high and the accuracy is low. As we compare it to model K2, K2 has higher accuracy since it incorporates maxpooling and batch normalization for each convolutional layer. Batch normalization slows the convergence as a result of which we would require more epochs to converge to a higher accuracy. Since we had to keep the epochs unchanged, the model K1 acquired a lower accuracy in the given fixed number of epochs compared to K2. Therefore, we observe and conclude that Batch normalization should be a standardized operator with convolutional nueral network in order to reduce cconvergence time and reduce computation.
